

<worksheet xml:id="A26_Intro-to-definite-integrals">
  <title>Math 150  Activity 26: Intro to definite integrals</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Water flows into a tank at <m>g(t)</m> liters per minute.
        The graph of <m>g(t)</m> is pictured below.
      </p>

      <sidebyside>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\begin{axis}[
            xlabel=\(t   (\si{min})\),
            ylabel=\(g(t)   (\si{L/min})\),
            xmin=0, xmax=4,
            ymin=0, ymax=4,
            xtick={0, 1, 2, 3, 4},
            ytick={0, 1, 2, 3, 4},
            minor x tick num = 1,
            minor y tick num = 1,
            ]
            \addplot[domain=0:8, style=very thick]{
            3 + (2*x-1)*(2*x-5)*(2*x-7)/50
            };
            \end{axis}\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            Find <m>L_4</m> to estimate the total volume of water that enters the tank during the first 4 minutes.
          </p>
        </task>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            Find <m>L_8</m> to estimate the total volume of water that enters the tank during the first 4 minutes.
          </p>
        </task>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            Compare your estimates.
            Which is better?
          </p>
        </task>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        The symbol <m>\displaystyle\int_0^4 g(t) \; dt</m> represents the area between the graph of <m>g(t)</m> and the <m>t</m>-axis between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 4</m>.
      </p>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\begin{axis}[
          xlabel=\(t   (\si{min})\),
          ylabel=\(g(t)   (\si{L/min})\),
          xmin=0, xmax=4,
          ymin=0, ymax=4,
          xtick={0, 1, 2, 3, 4},
          ytick={0, 1, 2, 3, 4},
          minor x tick num = 1,
          minor y tick num = 1,
          ]
          \addplot[domain=0:8, style=very thick]{
          3 + (2*x-1)*(2*x-5)*(2*x-7)/50
          };
          \end{axis}\end{tikzpicture}]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>\displaystyle\int_0^4 g(t) \; dt</m>.
        The graph is reproduced for your convenience.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain what each of the definite integrals
        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x)\,dx</m> represents and explain how to find the units of measurement for it.
      </p>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int_{2005}^{2010} P(t) \, dt</m>,
          where <m>P(t)</m> is the rate at which the world's population is growing in year <m>t</m>,
          in billions<nbsp />of people per year.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int_0^8 s(x) \, dx</m>,
          where <m>s(x)</m> is the rate of change of salinity
          (salt concentration)
          in <m>\si{g/L/cm}</m> in sea water,
          and where <m>x</m> is the depth below the surface of the water in <m>\si{cm}</m>.
          Note that <m>\si{g/L/cm} = \si[per-mode=fraction]{\gram\per\liter\per\centi\meter}</m>.
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <p>
    This graph shows that water may be either entering or leaving the tank,
    according as <m>g(t)</m> is positive or negative.
    Suppose that it holds <m>\SI{20}{L}</m> when <m>t = 0</m>.
  </p>
  <image>
    <latex-image>
      <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\begin{axis}[
